ess while tending a relative’s children in a place far away from home – and, apparently just as debilitating, away from the company of other women. Her experiences and reactions throw fresh light on the lives lived by Plains Cree women on the Canadian prairies over much of the twentieth century. The late Sarah Whitecalf (1919–1991) spoke Cree exclusively, spending most of her life at Nakiwacîhk / Sweetgrass Reserve on the North Saskatchewan River. This is where Leonard Bloomfield was told his Sacred Stories of the Sweet Grass Cree in 1925 and where a decade later David Mandelbaum apprenticed himself to Kâ-miyokîsihkwêw / Fineday, the step-grandfather in whose family Sarah Whitecalf grew up. In presenting a Cree woman’s view of her world, the texts in this volume directly reflect the spoken word: Sarah Whitecalf’s memoirs are here printed in Cree exactly as she recorded them, with a close English translation on the facing page. They constitute an autobiography of great personal authority and rare authenticity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Multiple languages.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCree IndiansxSocial life and customsy20th century. 0aCree IndianszSaskatchewanxHistoryy20th century. 0aCree IndianszSaskatchewanxReligion. 0aCree languagevTexts. 0aCree literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAhenakew, Freda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWhitecalf, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhitecalf, Ted, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolfart, H.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolfart, H.C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitl